73,http://www.armslist.com/posts/501073,For Sale:  80% Lower Receiver for AR-15,"North East, Mall of GA, Atlanta, Georgia",$ 125,"Listed On: Saturday, August 4, 2012",Gun,no type,no type,no type,no type,"A couple years ago I bought this 80% lower from a guy I knew, thinking I could find some way to finish it out on my own.  It's just been sitting around collecting dust.  I figured I could at least sell it and buy more ammo for other things!
A little bit about this lower.  It is not your standard 80%er.  This one has the mag well, AND fire control pocket milled out already!  The 20% left to do is the following.
-Tap threads for buffer tube.
-Drill hole for buffer retention pin.
-Drill and tap threads for pistol grip.
-Drill both fire control holes.
-Drill Safety selector hole.
-Drill bolt catch roll pin hole.
-Drill both front and rear take down pin holes.
-Drill front and rear spring/detent holes for take down pins.
-Drill trigger guard pin holes.
-Drill indentation for buttstock collar.
Now, this looks like a long list; but notice that all of this is ""drill,"" not ""mill.""  That means with proper blue prints and a good micrometer, you can do this in any old drill press.

I'd be glad to meet during the evening sometime at the Mall of Georgia or any of the surrounding areas.  I work out in Commerce, so meeting after work is a must.  If you're an Athens resident I'm also in that area a bunch to.  I'd be glad to try and meet you over the lunch hour on the north side of town.

I paid $150 for this in 2008 during the height of Obama's election.  I'm needing $125 in cash, or else $100 in trade value for other gun related items.  Ammo, AR mags, Glock mags, ect...  Won't hurt to ask me.
Thanks everyone!"

It has a Match Grade trigger, two piece full rod guide, Mag guide, 2 magazines, and other custom features.  Will include the original Match barrel and spring.  You will definitely appreciate this 1911!  Great HOG Gun too!
Some information on the .460 Rowland to familiarize you--

The .460 ROWLAND has external dimensions identical to the .45 ACP case with the exception of length. With safety as a prime consideration, the .460 ROWLAND case is approximately 1/16 of an inch longer (.460 ROWLAND case length is .957 on.) than the .45ACP case, to prevent chambering in an unmodified .45 ACP handguns.  Internally, the .460 ROWLAND case is much stronger than the .45 ACP case with an entirely different design and pressure capacity.  Loading information for the .460 should NEVER be interchanged or substituted in .45 ACP cases; however, .45 ACP loads may be used in the .460 ROWLAND cases and fired in properly chambered guns with no apparent difficulty.

Tests show that a 230 grain .460 round reaches a velocity of 1340 fps, while a standard 240 grain .44 Remington Magnum round reaches a velocity of only 1180 fps. The energy in ft/lbs is 917 for the .460, compared to 741 for the .44 magnum.

The .460 ROWLAND loaded round overall length (OAL) is the same as the .45 ACP OAL to allow use of standard magazines and common accessories.  It has been established that pressure limits for the .460 ROWLAND cartridge at or below 40,000 Copper Units of Pressure (CUP), and believes this to be the optimal pressure limit for available guns and components.
